<Content>Extremely Rude Staff After an extremely unpleasant stay at the JW Marriott, we switched hotels over to the Conrad Miami (two blocks away). We were very impressed with the night staff, Nicos and Omar. They made us feel extremely pampered and treated us the way a five star hotel should treat guest. Nicos told us that we could check in at 11:00 and that every thing was going to be handled. The following morning, when we went to check in, the one and only front desk staff member told me that I could not check in. I told her that I had a two year old who needed a nap and the we just checked out the the JW Marriott. She finally gave in (but had an attitude about it) and allowed us to check in. BUT THEN she placed me to the side and helped two other guest and made me wait. This was unacceptable for a five star hotel. Then I had previously arranged for a roll away bed. The front desk staff yelled at me and told me I'm suppose to charge you for a roll away bed..just be lucky I'm not charging you!! This was very inappropriate. Did I mention when we arrived at the hotel, the doormen did not greet us at all. The valet guy had to help us with our luggage, while the bell captain staff talked with a friend of his. I did not mind the two sets of elevators to reach our room with a great view, but it could be a hassel for some. The front desk staff was incredibly inexperienced, rude and not guest friendly. There never seemed to be enough staff at the front desk. I had to wait in line a long time every time I had either a simple question or checked in or out. After all of that, i did speak to the Front Desk Manager, Harold, who did everthing that he should have done. He made every attempt to make our stay more delightful. And, after talking with Harold, I would like to give the Conrad Hilton a second chance. The hotel is excellent with the atmosphere and the quality; the staff needs either better training or more experience. I am returning in a few months and will give them another chance. I feel they have the potential to do better. The city has many other upscale hotels (the Ritz, Tides, Delano and Lowes) that we have experienced in the past. I know that the Conrad will do better. 
